A look at a cloud-resident data service: HSDS (HDF Scalable Data Service)

Vince Carey1

Source: vignettes/htxlook.Rmd
htxlook.Rmd

HumanTranscriptomeCompendium: First glimpses

suppressPackageStartupMessages({
library(BiocStyle)
})

Following on Sean Davis’ BigRNA project, in which 181000+ RNA-seq studies in NCBI SRA are uniformly processed by a salmon-based workflow, we transformed the gene-level quantifications to HDF5 and loaded them into the HDF Scalable Data Service (HSDS).

The RESTful SummarizedExperiment view

The restfulSE package uses rhdf5client to implement a DelayedArray/SummarizedExperiment interface to this collection of transcriptomes.

More on metadata

To obtain the metadata on a study in this compendium, we can use the OmicIDX API. The following function retrieves available information, given an SRA study accession number:

meta_by_study = function(study_accession,
   urlbase = "https://api.omicidx.cancerdatasci.org/sra/studies/") {
 md = jsonlite::fromJSON(txt=
   url(paste0(urlbase, study_accession, "/runs?size=500")), flatten=TRUE)
 ans = tibble::as_tibble(md$hits)
 attr(ans, "cursor") = md$cursor
 ans
}
m1 = meta_by_study("SRP012682")  # GTEx

The metadata structure varies across studies and across samples within studies. The following moves towards a more regular structure by pivoting the nested key-value pairs in sample attributes.

sa = m1 %>% dplyr::select(accession, sample.attributes) %>%
   tidyr::unnest(sample.attributes) %>%
   tidyr::pivot_wider(names_from='tag', values_from='value')
#> Warning: Values are not uniquely identified; output will contain list-cols.

#> * Use `values_fn = length` to identify where the duplicates arise
#> * Use `values_fn = {summary_fun}` to summarise duplicates
tail(sort(table(unlist(sa$`body site`))))
